The Czech Social Democrats in Prague do not know Voldemort or the "Konditorei".
The new members of the Prague City Council from the ČSSD will obviously have to overcome certain language barriers in order to be able to understand their old-new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague City Council and the city council.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz has "tapped" members of the new Council from the ČSSD a bit as they master the notorious slang that has become established in recent years, when the current coalition partners in Prague were at the helm.
The coded vocabulary, introduced by the Prague political elite in the late era of Mayor Pavel Bém, is borrowed from some of the most well-known actors, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, the new councils were somewhat in the dark about what these new terms meant.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
I don't know.
"I'm rather a newcomer to Prague politics", Lukáš Kaucký, the new mayor for culture, said when asked about the "patron vocabulary".
But the mayor, Karel Březina, a veteran politician, reacted in a similar way.
Take the term "golf hole".
"That's the only expression of those you present to me here that I use occasionally".
"Otherwise I don't like slang".
From the vocabulary published by the daily Aktuálně.cz in June this year, ahead of the ODS election congress, the editorial team selected six terms, especially those notoriously associated with the Prague Magistrat.
The Social Democrats should define the terms "Voldemort", "Prague's largest golf hole", "going to the pastry shop", "beef cuts", "betraying the capital" and "bleached".
Three Prague councillors agreed to the test, and the fourth - Antonín Weinert, the future head of the Prague school system - promised to take part in the discussion but did not even take the listeners.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, refused the test from the outset.
"I don't care about these things and how the Civic Democrats talk to each other, I don't judge".
"What is important to me is how we understand each other in our programmes", he said.
As indicated above, Lukáš Kaucký allegedly did not recognise in the above-mentioned headline that the subject was the influential businessman and friend of the former mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek.
The term "Voldemort" tells Kaucky nothing, and the only term he got correct on the test was "the biggest hole in Prague golf".
"This is the Blanka Tunnel", says Kaucký, adding, "but I know more about it from the newspaper".
And he joked, "I guess I'll have to take a language course".
The "golf hole" is then correctly deciphered as the Blanka tunnel not only by Matador Karel Březina but also by the councillor for environmental affairs, Lukáš Plachý.
The Socialists also know who Voldemort is, and Lukáš Plachý even knows where he is and what it means to go to the pastry shop.
"I think that means going to some Prague catering establishment", Plachy is pretty close to the solution to the puzzle, knowing that this is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
However, in agreement with Březina, he claims that he has acquired this knowledge from the newspaper rather than that he has this vocabulary.
The question is whether the Commission will be able to take the necessary steps to ensure that the Community's policies are properly implemented.
"I've asked my colleagues, but obviously we don't really have that".
"We call each other by name, sometimes we also use abbreviations or nicknames", says the chairman of the Prague ČSSD, Petr Hulínský - nicknamed "Hulda" by his party mates.
"At school I was called Bříza (Birch), but I don't know if my colleagues call me that", says Karel Březina, who gives us his nickname.
The newspaper Deník Aktuálně.cz tried the name and look - it works.
The Councilman Weinert is the party's friend, the "grandpa" or less the "old man", the representative Miroslav Poche, who drew attention to himself by his party sponsorship schemes before the elections, is called "Igráček" (a well-known Czech Lego figure) by some colleagues.
The only thing the Social Democrats allow in party parlance is nicknames.
Hulínský is said not to like being called "Hulda", but Deník Aktuálně.cz registered another nickname for the Prague chairman.
His nickname "Doctor of Rubber-stick Rights" is supposedly related to Petr Hulínský's earning his Doctor of Juris at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and has published a brochure
Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually share some social characteristics.
They are more likely to be older, unemployed, for example because of ill health, single and childless.
If one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become a danger to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate".
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, because they help in the work and give birth", describes a religious sister who cares for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their communities in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for that reason, he published a pamphlet to stop the "witch hunt".
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso are illiterate", the newspaper Der Standard pointed out, pointing to the dilemma of literacy.
But accusations of witchcraft are common in other African lands.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured petroleum on her and set her on fire.
This incident was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the matter was merely a coincidence.
According to their version, the oil is ignited, used for ritual anointing.
This was after the group tried to "cast out an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by the people here regardless of their education.
"Soul-eaters were once as much a danger as they are today", said a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso, quoted by the Standard.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to de-escalate the witch hunt, the Gambian president himself has been involved in a good way in the past year.
"President Yahya Jammeh started a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, as they were allegedly involved in her death and now would try to kill the president himself by black magic".
"He called on shamans from nearby Guinea, who accompanied police, soldiers and the president's bodyguards, to forcibly abduct women and men who had been arbitrarily arrested from Gambian villages and take them to the president's farm in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the people were forced to drink a plant-based excrement that was hallucinogenic but also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the people arrested did not survive their stay on the farm.
Only because of international pressure were the nearly one thousand prisoners released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the oven - yet pays higher rent
An elderly man is leaving the customer center of the company RPG Byty of "coal baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm was a briefcase with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughters' apartments and his son's, who is serving a prison sentence.
All three have been given a rent increase as part of the so-called "deregulation".
Instead of 3500 crowns a month, the son is to raise 4100 crowns next year for a two-room apartment with a second-class kitchen.
"And there's no running hot water in the apartment, and you have to heat it in a simple coal oven", he angrily points his finger at his son's new lease, which he has a power of attorney to sign.
"But what - I signed", he says half disagreeing and half resigning.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until 7 December, when it intends to publish a guide on how to proceed against such contracts.
But the man just waves off.
"One says this, the other says that", he makes a gloomy face.
The Ostrava region is thus becoming a large "de-regulation laboratory".
After the New Year, this deregulation will affect most rental housing in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not yet paid a market-based rent.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "lab" personally.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full at nine o'clock this Tuesday morning.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a pager.
"Rent 2011", says a special touch screen light.
You type a few words, and the machine spits out a license plate.
We barely deciphered the number "157" and it's already beeping on the big display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it's your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enter the waiting room to ask for rent, but the rush in the waiting room is not apparently for the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance matters and the like.
From mid-November, the envelopes containing the new lease agreements will be floating in the mailboxes of most of the tenants of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG's portfolio in the Ostrava region.
The RPG Byty offers them in the letter an increase in rent from about 15 to 38 percent.
The special counter for new rentals in the customer centre has been open since 18 November.
"The campaign is running for a little over a week, so this is just the beginning", the ladies behind the counter reply after a moment's hesitation when the "client" turns out to be a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former miners' apartments are a hot topic.
Before the elections, the vice-president of the Ostrava-based parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek of the ČSSD, had taken up this issue quite loudly, no wonder the newspapers are full of it today.
"Twenty years I want them to have a new floor".
"They couldn't even change a single pair of toilet glasses", the man mentioned at the outset says.
So far, according to the employees, pensioners are the main ones waiting in line at the counter to make sure that they really get the promised rent reduction that RPG promises them if they sign up for the special offer in time.
The half-reduced February rent will also be granted to other tenants who sign the new lease by 15 December.
But so far, the "de-regulation switch" in Havířov is anything but overloaded with demand.
"Of the 360 customers yesterday, only about 40 to 50 of the rent in 2011 was due here", the local telephone exchange officials estimate.
RPG offers individual rental agreements on its websites and on wall panels where necessary.
If the parties do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
"This is not intended to be a threat, but is to be understood as information about the only possible and fully legitimate legal process", RPG explains on its website.
"No one is going to court here", says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man on the street in front of the customer center agrees with her at least in part.
"I have 13,000 (krona) of pension, 5,000 of which I have left for food, where should I get the money for a court case", he thinks.
That's when the employee gets insecure.
"Let's see what we can do".
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and so people are still waiting", she says.
The regulated rent ends in most of the Czech Republic on New Year's Day 2011 and according to RPG Byty the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing level of rent is not even enough to maintain the housing fund", argues Pavel Klimeš, the director of the housing portfolio of the company RPG Byty and - the neglect of the housing fund, which was criticized by the bored tenants, is the main reason for the rent increase according to the homeowners.
While RPG was able to invest 4 billion in the housing sector from the rent received between 2005 and 2010, it is estimated that it will invest 5,2 billion in the four years from 2011 to 2014.
On the large LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstered seats in the Havířov waiting room, a few red-lit information flashes in between.
'The rent increases in 2011 of 15% and below concern 31 200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of the apartments of RPG.'
"Always this means no more than CZK 7.50 per square meter per month", reads the LCD screen.
Only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio increase the rent by 38 percent.
"In these cases, it is the increase in extremely low rental prices of CZK 19,66 per square metre", argues RPG.
With 2600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive rents up sharply, but will be gradual over four and eight years.
What is more, the company imposes another obligation on itself: all the income from the rent increase (see diagram) the company wants to put back into the apartments, especially in heat savings - in new windows and in the thermal insulation.
- but they should primarily benefit those people who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects saw that the office also includes a kindergarten.
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with all the amenities that go with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys, and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architecture firm Arch.Design, whose studios are home to a number of famous Brno buildings, had been planning the premises for its company's mini-kindergarten from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building.
It is a wise move, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is keen to get the designers and architects back to work as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility of working part-time, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social programme.
It is easier for civil engineers and architects to balance their demanding job with childcare.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten in the factory is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and the State budget of the Czech Republic.
This financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be procured and qualified personnel and operations provided for for a period of two years.
After the funding has been used up (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for a further 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a year, with the help of Economy Rating.
The children are cared for by qualified staff on a full-time basis - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can be attended by children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only five children are allowed to be present at a time, but several children alternate each other during the day.
The kindergarten is flexible and tailored to the needs of the parents, and the children of all employees have the same rights to use the kindergarten, regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the content of the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children here not only play, but above all they are taught excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool, and they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games but also with a computer at the children's disposal.
What is more, the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive work environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time, and this eliminates the stress of late pick-up from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also formed here.
Arch.Design thus joined the ranks of Czech companies which offer clear benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and which use such programmes to boost their personnel marketing.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are ripped up fish moles.
This is the Casa Batlló by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local inhabitants nicknamed the house with its organic forms "Bone House".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house is filled with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind us of nature and living creatures.
Only when you look closely do you notice that everything is governed by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole facade seems more plastic, more dramatic, and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same fluid lines and intertwined shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood imitates window frames, railing, doorway ornaments, and even viewpoints and bars.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district, on the busy Passeig de Grácia shopping street, was built by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese, after the conversion of an 1877 house.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but eventually he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
But Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló rental house alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his sketchboard that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, many other sculptors and artists also contributed to the design of the facade.
Working together on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Soon after its completion, the house was given its organic forms by the local inhabitants, who nicknamed it "Bone House".
Others called it the "going house" because of the special window-opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre is already suggesting their 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes of the time and did not allow himself to be misled by them.
He obtained the city's building permit before construction began, but the details he gave about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded relief.
The councillors also found that the building with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, no changes were made, on the contrary - just 15 days after the district requested this, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted promptly.
The owner of the house moved into the lower floors himself.
The gallery on the second floor contained a social salon, while the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment were on the third floor.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the rebuilding eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part is completely connected by the opening of the doors of the salon, and thus a larger company could chat comfortably without having to forego a certain intimacy in more intimate conversations.
Gaudí's renovation also added a rather unusual roof and two more floors, in addition to a new facade.
Gaudí's play with light and the blue and white glazed tiles that line the courtyard and the lighthouses are also impressive.
The combination of these two colors gives all floors of the house the best light.
He simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight in the opposite direction.
The Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is now open to the public.
The first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly lucrative business, the visits were continued, and even extended to other common areas and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price of the visit is not a penny, however, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get 20 percent discount.
This is more than the entrance fees for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to befriend one of the house's inhabitants and visit him at home.
Women have different needs than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the bed - so mattress and rust make the best bed.
These must, however, be harmoniously complemented in order to meet the needs of the individual user.
Many factors are involved in the selection - the sleeper's weight, height, health, and, not least, the sex.
Equally important is the interior, where mattresses and rust are subordinated.
What's the typical example?
In a weekend home that is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
- And they should be turned regularly.
If they lack ventilation channels in their core and are on a solid surface, moisture builds up, so it is possible that mold may form underneath them.
Of course, what you are used to also plays a role in the choice.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft surface are common, you will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"I've had all the hockey players who've come back from the NHL complain to me that they can't sleep here anymore".
"For their shrunken shoulders, heels, and hips, they simply need a soft coating of visco foam".
"I also recommend it to people with diabetes, who have a nervous system disorder that makes them unable to receive the 'information' from their joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, a specialist in upholstery.
So years ago, I got many ice hockey players and other customers these mattresses with visco foam.
"Today, this is no longer a problem, as such mattresses are offered by manufacturers such as Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex and the Czech manufacturer Tropico".
And you don't have to be a famous hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the heat it absorbs, in other words, it sticks to the warm body.
Nowhere is it pressing, at night you don't roll around like after a hard fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also provides protection against decubitus (burn).
When choosing the mattress size, the length of the soles of the feet should still be added to the body size, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Men and women who are about six feet tall need a bed that's about six to seven feet long.
Each sleeper should have at least 90 cm of sleeping space, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example singles, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For your convenience and for any visitors.
Otherwise, the rule of thumb for the ideal bed width is: "If you lie on your back, there should be enough room for your slightly angled arms", advises Helena Prokopová, a master of upholstery and interior design who has been working on the subject of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years and who also lectures on this subject at technical schools.
If you have a double bed, you need your own mattress and your own bed, but be careful when you shop to ensure that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is no choice but to mount the grate at different heights, and this is not possible for every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, feather-shaped mattresses 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be on the moulding layer and the fine upholstery.
"You must not feel the feathers with your hands or when you sit down", warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
All-up beds with mattresses and bed linens like twins grown together have no place in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the linings cannot be washed, which is already the norm.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will slowly become a huge (and clogged) sieve.
For this reason, experts reject advertising that mattresses can last up to 25 years, or even a lifetime.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And so here is a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses that are 120 or 140 centimeters wide, you should not be afraid of the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is recommended to use a mattress saver that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers are now usually made with a rounded cap, so that when opened, you get two halves (very important for the washing process and the size of the washing machine!), the manipulation of larger mattresses, especially when done alone, often resembles the uneven fight between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a rust?
Get it out!
Or at most, a bed for unwelcome guests and for one night.
Even so, they should provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are none inside) and use mattresses with a spring skeleton and a minimum height of 15 cm with so-called pocket springs and fine upholstery.
Polyurethane mattresses are not suitable for such a base.
For non-adjustable lattice grills with 14 to 18 spring bars (lamellae), latex or sandwich mattresses (including combinations of latex and coconut, if applicable) are suitable, always with a larger number of lattice grills, i.e. 28 or more spring bars, with a loose support in the lumbar spine and the possibility of regulating the hardness of the lattice.
Adjustable slab grills do not include mattresses with spring skeleton, as they do not respond to ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring bars, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This is a special attachment of the spring bars which allows the spring bars to be pressed in or even angled so that they allow the sleeper's shoulder to sink in a specific place.
Especially for men with broad shoulders.
Some mattress manufacturers have even begun to use soft shoulder areas for "men's" mattresses.
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point elastic wing-fenders (lattoflex) or grates with point elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the tension.
- But if you use a bad (too big and full) pillow for the right mattress and rust, most of the benefits are lost.
Here again, a rule of thumb is that the pillow should support the head, with its tips reaching only to the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
The ideal pillow is a 50 x 60 cm pillow, as the Scandinavians like it.
In the side position, the head pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the rust or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the old straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their mixtures.
Even for mattresses, the new magic word is "organic".
Instead of using petroleum, natural oils - such as castor oil and soybean oil - are increasingly used to produce polyurethane foams.
I think soy is used by all the well-known manufacturers.
"The term 'organic' refers to mattresses whose core is made of materials of purely natural origin", explains Petr Vašíček of Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used in the manufacture of mattress covers - one of the first was Aloe Vera.
You can also use microcapsules that emit the fresh scent of forest or lavender when you sleep.
Here again, a distinction is made between man and woman.
While men use a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves to allow the mattress cover to absorb heat and cool the body, women use the covers to "warm up".
Red pepper extracts stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex is comfortable when sleeping.
What about today's favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are located.
But a good mattress costs 7,000 crowns and more.
Health mattresses, however, are usually subject to a lower VAT rate as they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to benefit from this advantage.
You see, saving on mattresses and rust is not so easy.
Occasionally, special offers are made by manufacturers and dealers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
The Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with visco-foam memory hidden in the frame for CZK 11,990.
The second one's free.
It was the material Tempur that ushered in the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at almost cosmic rates.
No wonder, they were designed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads during the launches.
Temperature becomes soft in warmth, but in cooler conditions it hardens again.
It adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes the body's pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure burn, but also for improving sleep comfort in general.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only in mattresses but also in other health products, such as special foot pads intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, the Eucatherm C foams, Twinsavers or similar products.
More and more parents want human-monitoring devices to keep their kids under control
Fear for their children is growing, and more and more parents are considering monitoring their children with GPS.
The system, originally designed to search for cars, is just as good at locating people, which would be helpful in such cases as the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but it is not expected to be larger than a wristwatch any time soon.
Many people are terrified by the disappearance of Anička and are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the price of compromising their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not a case of spying, but an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet had such a case".
"Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons", adds Pilin.
He says that the child should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children are highly creative about deliberately losing things when they don't want to be controlled".
"At first, parents had high expectations of mobile phones, but they are as easy to turn off as these new surveillance devices", says Ms. Bočková.
In her opinion, it is also debatable whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned kidnappings, the kidnapper will virtually always check that the child has any electronics with him or her that could be used to locate him or her".
"Today it's the phone".
"If such surveillance devices were to be widely used, they would also seek them out, as their sale would surely be accompanied by massive advertising".
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, she admits that similar devices may be helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Roberta Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both cars and people, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
'The device can be adjusted to report the position at certain intervals.'
"Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last location of the person concerned is available".
"More expensive devices even have a tiltmeter built in, which means that if you fall and remain motionless, the device will immediately send a warning indicating your position", Mr Čech claims.
