Longer index than ring fingers mean lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than their ring finger are evidently at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It's supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results suggest that the relative length of the fingers can be used as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly in men over the age of 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick's Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients, but also 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men were as likely to get prostate cancer as 19 percent of men with the same length of ring and index fingers.
However, for men whose index finger was longer than their ring finger, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men up to the age of sixty, by 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers mentioned, which are already forming in the prenatal period, evidently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is the one that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was only briefly aware of this study, but that he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "fully established".
