The democratic movement in Latin America is growing, as is the support for private enterprise.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These results are the result of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was carried out in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in the region.
Two facts stand out in particular in this year's survey of September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
And secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its key institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing at about 6% a year since 2002, the number of pro-democracy voters has risen from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Similar trends are evident in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year's sharp slump.
However, only half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Some 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with the democratic practice in their country, the same as last year but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% trust their country's congress and 45% their government, both figures corresponding to last year's figures but showing a marked increase compared with 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to promote democracy.
The fact that this trend continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that Latin American countries experienced only a brief recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor have been catered for by a stronger social network.
(According to reports this week from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America, the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year by 32 percent.)
However, there are considerable differences in sentiment from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread progressive mindset.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more pronounced and violent crime increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the survey began, many Latin American respondents see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Some 31% say that either they or a family member was a victim of a crime in the last year, but the figures have fallen from 38% last year to the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the increased support for the private and market economies: around 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% said that only the market economy could bring progress to their country, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela maintained this view (and 80% are in favour of a private sector), even though their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the highest weight in the region according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
In contrast, respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
