The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously thought to be essential for life.
"This organism has two possibilities".
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow".
"This makes it very special, even though it's almost a kind of 'alien' life form", said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
Up to now, six basic elements have been considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But scientists found that the bacteria in Mono Lake, California, continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"You wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report at Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study is looking at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed", explains Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another", added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she speculated that microbes exposed to both could possibly replace one element with another.
"The toxicity of arsenic is primarily due to its chemical similarity to phosphorus".
"It makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another".
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently from phosphorus, and it gets into our biochemical system, where it lubricates almost everything", explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to increasing levels of arsenic, and it adapted and grew.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but the fact that it can survive in arsenic also suggests that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
According to Jamie S. Foster, an associate professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has been no working example so far.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This suggests that life may have evolved differently from the early Earth", says Forster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
