Can courtesy connect the dots?
After a campaign of profanity and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of real bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before quickly returning to the battle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and top congressional officials did not break through the big issues that were being addressed during the so-called lame duck session, the session at the end of a term in which no decisions are made.
From what I hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different parties nor a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partial point-setting.
The public meeting of the President's deficit committee on Wednesday was likewise civilized, despite the political differences that still exist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months builds up a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to divide the members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one demanding from the other signs of cooperation and compromise, while the other is trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a new party war.
The meeting itself and the participants' assessment of it were therefore limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health care or expectations, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November election was a mild one in Washington, at least for a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die off again.
And that's good".
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution".
Bush's tax cuts are due to expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to keep some or all of them, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on the unemployment pay raise is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favoured tax cuts are for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting at the White House on Tuesday, there was increased optimism that these issues could be agreed during the lame duck session and at the same time the New START Treaty could be ratified.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January".
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation", he said.
We are also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-game, or shadow box, for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the makeup of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who served their formation.
As concerned as Republican leaders may be about playing too high a bet, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and reducing public expenditure.
Vice-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington, and have, in their own judgment, pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 out of 18 votes in the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the body, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two stages in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of party clashes, with Republicans challenging Obama over the budget, taxes and health care system, followed later by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will bring about this change?
The public opinion.
It's been proven that, despite the partisan nature of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, both parties must be careful about the public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
The bias and polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and it seems to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and congressional Republicans than it was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more consequential 2012 election.
In this respect, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
