Red Bull wins F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The cars are being upgraded with real-time software.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula One in 2004, its history in this exquisite universe has been marked by speed of surprise and success.
At first, no one paid attention to the newcomer, and despite his steep climb during the last seasons, everyone bet on the victory of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari at the final lap last November.
Without wanting to diminish the skills of German driver and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of Renault's engine, the "secret weapon" that put the Multi Siemens Red Bull in its hands and thus created a winning team has become a legend.
In reality, it is a high-performance process simulation software that the German company launched in 2007 for non-race-related purposes.
This computer program, known as PLM, has been used to develop assembly lines in factories around the world, power plants, and high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce or simulate a product or process accurately before it is actually built, in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, Head of Siemens' Industrial Division, explains that using this software in Formula 1 - Red Bull Factory can design and implement the changes and improvements that are detected in races and tests "in a matter of hours, almost in real time".
Russwurm states that in 1992 the racetracks had an average of ten technicians who could introduce no more than three or four improvements in a single season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly skilled young people, who use powerful computer systems to analyse and make any possible changes to the race cars.
The Siemens manager stated that the PLM software was capable of analysing and improving all components of Red Bull racing cars, with the exception of the engine, for which Renault claimed sole responsibility.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are being changed.
The changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this mad technical perfectionism is the $40 million a Formula One team is allowed to spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has set up its high-tech factory for the development and production of its racing cars in a location 30 miles from London.
These are two buildings where visits, particularly by journalists, are severely restricted.
Everything that happens there is top secret.
The crew consists of 580 people, including the two pilots, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true F1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion, Sebastian Vetell.
The enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts into the services of its participation on the racetracks hide other protagonists whose support is invaluable and whose notoriety is almost zero.
The plant's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, points out that five years ago, you could say that the advances in R&D for racing cars contributed 50 percent to the victory, and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today, the share values have changed, with technology accounting for 85 percent of the success, while the contribution of pilots is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computers, because they "are unpredictable gladiators".
