Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has decided to keep the euro, but at the same time it has set conditions for the whole European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a twofold response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has proposed new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment or the abolition of the 426 euro allowance for unemployed persons who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the administration of the Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the Deputy Prime Minister, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the one responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is foreseen that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the preservation of the long-standing traditions of many of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second is the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark, which, although it sounds like science fiction at the moment, is supported by a large part of the public, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is to reform the euro in accordance with German proposals, which means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishing countries that break the rules; possibly suspending payments to some countries and extending the cost of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been for some time now, so there are no excuses.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created deficit incentives and the German government pulled out of the sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to rescue Greece.
At the time, this was heavily criticized, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion, was absolutely against a bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel has again come out with a clear position: she is calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it fuelled the Irish crisis and all that followed.
But their proposal, albeit a bit sweet, was accepted and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union which will enable these measures to be implemented from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures must be taken now - the old way of working of the euro will no longer exist from this date on.
2013 will be the birth of a new currency area, where countries that do not comply will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare insolvency, and in this case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must pursue a hard course of growth, with high saving and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and building with huge holes in the balance of payments, as suggested by Spain during the boom years, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would be bad at not understanding it.
It's not just about bringing the deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope the current turmoil will turn into a more calm one.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in one's own home has begun to take shape.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything will change.
Among the possibilities considered is that we should have to leave the euro area, which is full of countries with little standing.
In that case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sports and circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to evade a penalty.
The alleged suspension of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has led to much speculation about whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is common knowledge, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already won clearly) and played several fouls to get the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfil the prescribed sanction in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next stage of play without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee fined the club's coach, José Mourinho, two games and the players involved different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that are followed in this sport.
Part of the debate over the case depicted is due to the fact that a team from the football club Real Madrid (which preys on nobility and honor in its anthem and has punished its players on other occasions for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
The debate is, in any event, whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute an evasion of the rules.
The damage to sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sporting spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect which was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of clean play is to prevent the opposing players from taking unjustified advantage of the opposing team.
The paradox of the actions of the Real Madrid players is that they do not correspond to what we normally understand as foul play or circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not committed in secret to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasised that neither the rival was put at a disadvantage nor any advantage was claimed for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club doesn't have those players.
The obvious advantage is that players start the next round of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it's a long-term advantage, to a certain degree uncertain, because the team could eventually be eliminated, and also the players get a penalty and go into the second card cycle, where they are eliminated because they accumulate one card less than in the first cycle.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
In the end, such approaches are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which includes strategic decisions to get the most out of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a penalty (which would actually be a clear case of breach), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between patenting and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of patenting.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of rule transfer provoked.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less of an ethical nature than of an aesthetic one.
The bidding campaign for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar has caused an avalanche of reservations this year on December 16 and 17.
The parties paid for by employees themselves are spreading. They do not want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the Turrón and the Christmas lottery, there are also group dinners in the run-up to Christmas, which fuel Barcelona's restaurant and leisure industry, but as a result of the economic crisis they are triggering a price campaign to catch the large customer segment: almost all want to spend between 20 and 30 euros for a lunch or dinner, the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations confirm.
To complicate the accounting a bit more, the calendar (New Year's Eve falls on a Friday) has dropped all orders to the week of December 13, resulting in an avalanche of dinner reservations on two top floors (the 16th and 17th) and almost no orders in the week before.
Since 2008, when the bad times began, many companies have stopped group dinners for budgetary reasons.
In order not to abandon this tradition, many workers pay for it out of their own pocket.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks of exposure to radioactive substances.
The representative of the umbrella association has not yet dared to predict what the holidays will be like this month.
"People think it over ten times before they make a reservation".
"They like to go out, but they pay a lot of attention to prices", he says.
Business will be good for those who "offer quality at good prices with good service", he adds, reminding us that customers save in times of crisis, which is why prices around €25 are most in demand.
A survey of several central restaurants shows that the evening of December 17th is leading to the collapse of the vendors.
The Soteras Group says that demand for this Friday, with the intention of spending less than 30 euros, will be booming.
Another leading group, Andilana, which operates 16 restaurants in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), has seen the peculiarity of the calendar lead to early bookings, even from the beginning of November.
