AN Grup, which manages El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and a total of 23 shops, is not losing its optimism after the second quarter saw revenues return to a flourishing state and good prospects for Christmas business, albeit concentrated on a few days.
Sources in the group point out that the 18th will also be an overactive day with groups of friends celebrating before Christmas.
The six group menus have been supplemented by a Christmas menu for 30 euros or more as a price hit, giving the impression that customers are willing to spend 10 percent more than last year and in return want more details, such as Cava.
In some companies, green shoots are also seen sprouting, which gives the impression that the group meals are back on the upswing.
On the other side of the umbrella association Fecasarm (with affiliates such as the Bar, Restaurant and Leisure Association of Barcelona), the Vice-President, Enric Gomà, is confident that he can see the end of the tunnel and notes that the reservations are quite "vibrant" overall, although the customers "make a maximum".
But the fun of the party hasn't diminished, no matter who pays.
Pakistan's nuclear program is a matter of great concern in the United States
Islamabad is making nuclear weapons "faster than any other country".
WikiLeaks revelations confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The contents of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department, revealed by the Wikileaks website, confirm the enormous concern Washington has over Pakistan's nuclear program.
Besides the clarifying and juicy details provided by the documents on the content of the talks and the thinking of the accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad, they reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security is not being strengthened but, on the contrary, is "decreasing", and that the unstable Asian country is producing more nuclear weapons "at a faster pace than any other country".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but are stored in order to make it more difficult to destroy them in the event of a possible attack - is causing Washington to have sleepless nights.
In a report before the visit of former National Security Council chief James Jones, Ambassador Anne W. Patterson in Pakistan lists the following risks: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area attacked by the Taliban, the likely dispersal of nuclear material and the vulnerability of nuclear material transport".
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is no longer seen as excessive and a reason for caution by the United States and Russia.
"Pakistan needs to recruit strictly religious personnel to guard the nuclear facilities; due to the low level of education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who are involved in nuclear or missile programs", said Yuri Korolev, an expert from the Russian Foreign Ministry, in a meeting with his North American counterparts.
What's new about the documentation revealed by Julian Assange's web portal is that the cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation is waning and the pace at which Pakistan is building nuclear weapons is increasing.
In May, an embassy office, which describes communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", said: "There is often no transparency; offers of help are not answered or rejected".
In another report, Peter Lavoy, a South Asia intelligence official, confirms that "despite economic disaster, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at the fastest rate of any other country".
Ambassador Patterson asks Washington to "clear" to the commander-in-chief during a visit by the commander-in-chief, General Ashfaq Kayani, that "Pakistan's army must cease its tacit support of terrorist groups".
In the hunt for the WikiLeaks boss
Obama appoints a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further revelations.
Interpol is issuing a red alert to track down and locate Assange.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, is a complicated maze in which the facts are difficult to unravel.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a "red alert" for the "finding and prosecution" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Besides, it's not new, it's from November 20th.
Nor does it have to do with the recent disclosure of over four million diplomatic documents from the United States, but with the sexual abuse allegations the Australian has to face in Sweden.
The lawyer for the founder of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, also assures that "the police would know where and how to contact Mr Assange".
The international police authority based in Lyon, France, issued the order on 20th July at the request of Sweden, but it was not made public until yesterday after receiving the authorization from the Swedish authorities.
The 188 countries of Interpol are instructed to identify and locate Assange "in order to arrest him and extradite him".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual under a red alert, many member states consider the red alert a release for arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move outraged Assange's lawyers, who gestured a letter informing them that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder was willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange requested to leave Sweden and was given permission by the prosecutor, who is compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's head of security.
"This is like a hunt, not like a legal prosecution", the letter accuses.
While the world is searching for him - and his mother from Australia is asserting her son's innocence - Assange is in an unknown location, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype from an undisclosed location, in which he requested the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN, in violation of international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign", he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has appointed a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
The attempt by President Barack Obama's spokesman to reduce the attention paid to Assange is in stark contrast to the views expressed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House National Security Committee starting in January, has urged the State Department to investigate the possibility of listing WikiLeaks as a terrorist organization "to seize its funds and prosecute anyone who supports or contributes to it".
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, went further, and had to retract his statement that Assange had to be "murdered".
"Obama would have to turn it into a target and use a drone or something".
The one who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and potential presidential candidate.
"Whoever leaked information to the government is guilty of treason and anything that is not an execution is too mild a punishment", he told Fox News.
Puigcercós looks with a wink at the Carod
The Republican leader allows the party to hold a secret vote on his continuance in office.
Huguet proposes a more pluralist government and the end of the principle of the plenary assembly.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe to avoid for the tenth time an internal riot in the ranks of the ERC, which has lost 11 deputies and half the votes.
The party chairman is aware that his threat of resignation is not enough for those close to former party leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of this sector is now as weak as its mentor himself and will not give him the same headache as other former currents.
That is why the leader of Esquerra is trying to win over the new critics with a wink, which would secure his position until the next local elections.
For starters, yesterday he announced that the more than 200 regional councillors of the ERC could speak in secret about his continuing in office.
With ballots, not with a raised hand.
If the carodians wanted to pass a ticket to the president, they could do so without fear of reprisals.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid the impression of division and submission in his person.
In several interviews he confirmed that he would not feel confirmed with half the votes plus one, and he added without stating percentages that a result "in the Bulgarian style" would not be good either.
Carod's supporters are demanding more from the president than just the party's handing over his office, a gesture that is not enough given Puigcercós' control of the highest body of Congress.
But since they don't have a majority to force resignations, they'll agree with the board on a course of action between now and May.
They expect to be able to contribute to the preparation of the strategic reorientation document which the management will submit to the Council for a vote on 18 December.
They intend to vouch for Puigcercós, who in return is expected to promise to move the congress to autumn 2011, which the party leadership already considers a fact.
The ERC's party chairman believes that "polyphony" is detrimental to stability and he is seeking to make the organization able once and for all to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors.
In this sense, the article signed by the acting Consul Josep Huguet in his blog is symptomatic.
Given that Puigcercós is an ideologue, the owner of Innovació considered it a fact that the party chairman is supported "in exchange for different goals".
He listed five, two of which are in the foreground.
First, the "restructuring" of the board so that it represents at least 90 percent of the party members, which means including new faces from Carod's circle.
The second one could be the big news.
Huguet proposes that the ERC should finally abandon the principle of the plenary as a way of functioning.
He is thus advocating a reform of the statutes to enable congresses to be held with elected delegates.
The end of the assembly model - an exception in the Spanish party system - is a source of obsession for Puigcercós' team, which has been fighting for it at the last two congresses.
In fact, at the 2008 trembling assembly, the party leadership was tasked with reviewing the principle of the plenary assembly at a congress to deal with the reform of the statutes.
The deadline has not yet been set, as the internal turmoil of recent years has made it unwise to deal with this matter.
Now, without the critical sectors on the lookout, it might be time to take up this matter again and shut it down for good.
