China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of China stated at COP16 that his country had made tremendous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and would maintain its promise to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is keeping its pledge to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to transform its industry.
He explained that over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
He said China would not change its goals but would work with the international community on this issue.
He explained that China's strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He said progress had been made in all areas, including the adoption of a new energy law last year which included targets for reducing emissions of gases.
On the other hand, it pointed out that in China, the state authorities had worked with the central government and the municipalities to achieve the energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction targets.
He also pointed out that several multiannual plans had already been started or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which had been launched over the past five years and had received investment from the United Nations (UN), the government and private hands.
He said that a project on climate change was also under way at provincial level, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving ones and another on mitigation and adaptation.
Martin Krol, the government's scientific adviser on climate change, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly believed.
He pointed out that per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for nine percent of the total contribution to environmental pollution.
He also said that the country was making unprecedented progress in energy use, with energy efficiency increasing by 20% over the past five years and another increase by 2020.
