Putting a finger in the wound with literature
The second round of 'The Lust for Language' was a walk where participants strengthened themselves for the story
"I understand the language sex thing, but... the finger in the wound, what is expected of me?" asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, who was opening the second round of Los Placeres de la lengua, a cycle celebrating Spanish-language literature, using the subtitle of her question on this occasion (at another event, the roundtable was dedicated to language sex, she explained).
The finger in the wound... "bringing us into trouble", the Argentine writer spat sweetly to the audience, which was composed mainly of young people who had gathered at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara (FIL) to attend the roundtable, moderated by Marisol Shultz, in which Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García Montero took part.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, which Shultz later described as a great story. Luisa tells in the first person and is the protagonist, who is looking to find out what a "wound" is, and goes from doctor to doctor, from which she does not get an answer, but she gets clues for the guide of her story.
She leaves the infectious disease doctor convinced: "Patience is not my strength, perhaps it is my wound".
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the trauma specialist, who took her breath away in the middle of the hallway, but who explained to her that wound is not a scientific term, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "the wound is the really open, the symbolic is the scar".
The protagonist of the story sighs relieved and concludes that she "only learned from the wound that it was really open and did not exist". But she is convinced that the pleasure in language and its traps are mixed.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both of them.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful story, which he called "The Praise of Invention", in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned but is discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back men who had traveled far, or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The story took a turn and reported on America, the great novel that from the beginning did not lack its own chronicler, and he quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticized the abundance of stories told by the conquerors.
"Cervantes, who invited us all, mocked the shamed witnesses who appeared in the stories presented as true, but otherwise the history of America would never have been told - with imagination that even the sense of shame was missing".
However, he points out that "it is the madmen and liars who imagine things best", and that is where reality and lie come closer together, where you can't tell which side the story belongs to, where fiction reaches its peak.
He actually calls it the Cervantes tradition.
"From him we inherited the story of being".
When it was Mayra Montero's turn, the writer commented and praised the variety of interpretations which had been contributed to by the invitation of the FIL to the round table 'The Finger in the Wound'.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican women dedicated their contributions to the great wound of social violence that is afflicting their country - as well as all of Latin America - as a result of the fight against drug trafficking.
"I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a tacit, not deliberately planned commitment", she explained, after stressing that literature is communication and commitment that builds up between the author and the readers as in a "chemical reaction".
The evening was decided by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also highlighted "that finger of the committed writer in the writer's wound".
He observed that in a fast-paced world, even intellectual habits and control of the mind are dogmatic, forgetting "that behind every affirmation there is a little no and behind every denial a little yes".
"To be in possession of our thoughts and reality, we must nuance: and nuancing often means putting our finger in the wound and harassing those who feel much more comfortable thinking in the form of caricatures, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuance, and also harassing the powerful who prefer to divide the world into black and white", he observed, inviting us to rediscover the meaning of writing.
