The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The visa applicant must present himself or herself at the visa service before the consular interview, thus reducing the costs and waiting times.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants must introduce themselves at the Visa Application Services (ASC) before their interview at the consulate.
The ASC staff shall record the applicant's biometric data, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, processing of the visa application and the transport service that handles the document.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for an application visa (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for handlers and investors.
Those who wish to extend their visas do not have to go to the consulate to interview them, but simply present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is collected at the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate will spend less time there than before.
Those applying for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the $26 service charge.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
