The discovery could prove the theory that in hostile environments previously thought uninhabitable, human-like creatures could exist. It was hypothesized that they could transform into intelligent living beings - like humans - if their living conditions improved.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too toxic for all life on Earth because of the lake's high arsenic content.
Somehow, the microbial community uses arsenic as a survival resource, and given this ability, the chances are that there could be similar life on other planets that don't have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize the arsenic, the astrobiologists say, "it is proven that there is actually another life form, a second life form, different from the one we know".
The Space Agency will announce the actual scope of its fund at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
