Worldwide plan for the renewal of lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancun a plan to renew lighting in homes, businesses and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions that is nearly one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the concrete large-scale projects which the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from the developed countries.
The main problem, in the form of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released into the earth by lighting, would be avoided, according to the plan presented yesterday, if the white-glowing bulbs, which have so far held a 50-70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better still, light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the world's fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we would have to subtract 5 Gt from this balance sheet to stabilize the rise by 2 degrees Celsius between now and 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing bulbs, 95 percent of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5 percent produces light.
The compact bulbs reduce energy consumption by 75%, and the new LED bulbs reduce this energy consumption by a further twofold.
The average duration of the compact fluorescent bulbs is between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as the one that the manufacturer Philips launched this week -- that company, by the way, participated in the UN study -- have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-glowing bulb, which gives a hint of the savings of the replacement plan to be implemented in 100 countries.
Apart from the fact that these completely new bulbs give off very little heat, they can also operate with a regular resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have pointed out that compact fluorescent light bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the producers provide a reception site.
However, the report says that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the benefits that each country would reap from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and 8 million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, which would cost Indonesia $2.5 billion to build.
