Vengeful Hackers and Eager Spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a twofold significance.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal which is merely a scandal in the sinful hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level and gives a glimpse of a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence agency (any nation) is made up exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what you read in any newspaper for months (except the ones owned by Berlusconi), and the terrifyingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been the material for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that the secret files should only consist of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that each work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what was already written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he did not know where news about the nonexistent would be found), but because those who practice occultism believe only what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
So are the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers as true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was there such a fuss about the revelations of these files?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows: that embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War, and since then, heads of state and government have been able to call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have turned into spy centres, with the exception of a few minor representative functions.
Any viewer of detective films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that you pretend to ignore it.
But the fact that it is repeated in public violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that a random hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Moreover, the scandal is not so much a victim's problem as a "scouring" one.
But let's focus on the profound nature of what happened.
In the old days, in Orwell's time, you could pool all the power like a Big Brother, controlling every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have since proved to be perfectly true, where you could control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel you visited, the highway you chose, and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
But when you consider what's happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can't escape the control of a hacker anymore, the control loop stops being one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen to be the citizen's avenger - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets survive?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secrets, since it exposes the public sphere; but to reveal, WikiLeaks-style, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to deprive her of any power.
WikiLeaks did not wrong Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this insult to such a mighty power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer post any kind of confidential information online - that would be like a street-corner poster.
But it is also obvious that with the current technology, it is futile to hope that we can keep confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state is traveling in an airplane and has contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private and exclusive relationships be maintained in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and novel, but I find myself forced to imagine the government agents, secretly and eagerly moving on uncontrollable march routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in mere memory, and furthermore, hiding the little written information they have received in their shoes.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically the Watergate espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology today is advancing like a cancer, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with wire.
The (analog) videocassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film tape by tape by reeling back and forth and revealing all the secrets of the editing, whereas the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro proportions.
High-speed trains take three hours to get from Rome to Milan, while flights take three and a half hours, including the transfer.
It is not unusual, therefore, that politics and communication technology are linked to cars and horses.
One last observation. What is it?
In the past, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that are demanding confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is flattering its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the compliance with the rapidly resolved financing commitments (also called 'fast start' or early financing) that have been implemented by the developing countries.
And the gross French charms are exposed.
The Copenhagen Accord pledged developing countries to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years, France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU has been working hard to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress reports from its Member States, press conferences, major side events, leaflets.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its very value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same thing at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money was to be 'new and additional' under the Copenhagen Treaty, to ensure that an additional contribution was made without detriment to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark that he considers best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen the 2009 target: international financing will be maintained and 150 million will be added over three years under the Fast Start funding.
Other countries have adopted similar guidelines, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of official development aid.
In contrast, France considered that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 was 'new and additional'.
In other words, there are no indications for the previous year's expenditure or for the global level of official development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to be complying with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into grants and loans.
There is no rule for this, and everyone chooses their own calculation mode.
Some, such as France, consider 1 € lent to be equivalent to 1 € donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emissions-related projects based on the most efficient technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro received as equivalent to a given euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the donor country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it 'respects' its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (€389.8 million) and giving away 8.5% (€36.1 million) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only EU country that makes large-scale loans.
Germany claims 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are 100% committed to donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends 1 euro to meet its obligations, France spends only 10 cents and understands this as a comparable commitment.
That's some good talk.
In general, France's fast-start financing is based on a double fraud: on the one hand, the development of the action over time, and on the other, the reality of the financial commitment.
France succeeds in making it appear that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation by the Treasury (since it seems that Bercy was the one who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect: firstly, within the EU (why do the other Member States continue to donate when there is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small issue in a relatively short time compared to the whole of the climate discussions.
But it may be too much of a drop in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that doesn't happen.
In any case, it is imperative that we learn the lesson from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of equitable compensation with the other countries of the European Union.
France could, above all, take the discussions on the subject of longterm financing forward (another crucial and currently debated topic): the question of the 'predictability' or the way in which its loans are booked cannot be avoided.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues at stake as it is on other matters.
The hope is therefore in the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of 'predictability' and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals a day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly the Movement for the Protection of the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which states that its results "do not represent a statistically significant value, given the small number of samples analysed, but rather an illustrative character of the problem being addressed", had purchased the food normally consumed at four meals by a child of about ten years of age plus a snack at the supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - were tested as well as lab-made sandwiches for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance is staggering: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe, as well as 37 endocrine disrupting substances, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical individual substance are not exceeded, this survey shows very well that the reality of the consumer being exposed to carcinogens or endocrine disrupting substances is a cause for concern", notes the association.
Already at breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three of the certain ones that have been shown to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The Brazilian apple, which was intended as a snack for the study, contained traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including the lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
Also, the meatballs, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analysis of the tap water revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected, and even the plastic dish used to microwave the meal was not untouched.
The final risk of this "polluting cocktail" to the consumer "is probably underestimated", says the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, "in view of the urgency of the situation", a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
